   "..."}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8132221669142685`*^9, 3.8132221794693403`*^9}, {
   3.8132222690385857`*^9, 3.813222292552426*^9}, {3.8132225103046436`*^9, 
   3.8132225357976294`*^9}, 3.813225530724597*^9, {3.8132268996594105`*^9, 
   3.8132268997936573`*^9}, {3.8132269718506794`*^9, 
   3.8132270598936987`*^9}, {3.813227090063882*^9, 3.8132270928942423`*^9}, {
   3.8132273687054873`*^9, 3.8132273956726027`*^9}, {3.8132274257354927`*^9, 
   3.8132274504676456`*^9}, {3.813227484968296*^9, 3.8132274916733313`*^9}, {
   3.813227717592659*^9, 3.813227799104663*^9}, {3.8132278524338465`*^9, 
   3.813227854764579*^9}, 3.8132279269606223`*^9, {3.81323366169593*^9, 
   3.813233662702242*^9}, {3.813676741631068*^9, 3.813676829221445*^9}, {
   3.8142067350871696`*^9, 
   3.8142067908071504`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c4ddfce0-caf1-434c-9f7f-\
fc3861dd7257"],

Cell["\<\
Note that the polyatomic case doesn\[CloseCurlyQuote]t really differ from the \
diatomic case in this respect; we just have more atomic orbitals. However, we \
know from general chemistry that in molecules, the bonds \
can\[CloseCurlyQuote]t always be explained by a simple combination of one \
atomic orbital from each atom; such a combination could never produce \
something like methane or even water. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8142067936434507`*^9, 
  3.814206912572139*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c834549a-4c9e-4a99-afd7-\
1817df21cb3b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "So how do we relate the true molecular structure to the atomic orbitals? A \
simple solution to this problem was championed by Linus Pauling nearly 100 \
years ago. Recall that we adopted the approximation that atomic orbitals only \
mix if they are similar in energy. In the first and second rows of the \
periodic table, the energies of the 2",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and 2",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbitals are relatively close, so we then should consider linear \
combinations of atomic orbitals that involve multiple 2",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and 2",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " orbitals on the same atom. This scheme is often referred to as orbital \
hybridization. In general, we could then write the contributions from the \
hybridized orbital as"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8142069699490795`*^9, 3.814207212238633*^9}, {
  3.8142716817942963`*^9, 
  3.8142716990549374`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"3abb3642-c5d2-4859-970e-\
c05b31cbcfd4"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"\[CapitalPhi]", "=", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["c",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "1"], 
    SubscriptBox["\[Phi]", 
     RowBox[{"2", 
      StyleBox["s",
       FontSlant->"Italic"]}]]}], "+", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["c",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "2"], 
    SubscriptBox["\[Phi]", 
     RowBox[{"2", 
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["p",
        FontSlant->"Italic"], "z"]}]]}], "+", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["c",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "3"], 
    SubscriptBox["\[Phi]", 
     RowBox[{"2", 
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["p",
        FontSlant->"Italic"], "x"]}]]}], "+", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["c",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "4"], 
    SubscriptBox["\[Phi]", 
     RowBox[{"2", 
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["p",
        FontSlant->"Italic"], "y"]}]]}]}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8142715408501225`*^9, 3.8142716264528427`*^9}, {
  3.8142716634962983`*^9, 3.81427166385531*^9}, {3.8142717090653296`*^9, 
  3.814271758882024*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"b8f3f97d-132a-4b4c-a5cc-\
57939d9199bd"],

Cell["\<\
this optimized hybrid orbital would then mix with the atomic (or hybrid) \
orbital on the other atom to yield the molecular orbital.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8142717643047514`*^9, 
  3.814271806592066*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"cb0d359f-0560-4372-98bb-\
e54d8c80f23d"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["sp",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " Hybrid Orbitals of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["BeH", "2"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "23914b75-cea7-4f0a-9fd5-bdc623a9943e"]
}], "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814271273630074*^9, 3.8142712932314315`*^9}, {
  3.8142780421409435`*^9, 
  3.81427804938619*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"eec6089e-3094-45a9-a187-\
97dff0f81c04"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s look at how we might explain the bonding of the \
linear molecule ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["BeH", "2"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "dce7fad9-67fa-4d3b-af71-903bc6ae5321"],
 " using an orbital hybridization approach. The ground state configuration of \
Be is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", 
   SuperscriptBox["s", "2"], "2", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["s",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "2"]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "57eca97d-0181-432d-9f1e-ee25a6346727"],
 ", and the 2",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " atomic orbital is similar in energy to the 1",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " atomic orbital of hydrogen. If we were to construct a diatomic molecule, \
we might think of combining the Be 2",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and H 1",
 StyleBox["s",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " atomic orbitals to make the \[Sigma] bonding and antibonding molecular \
orbitals. However, in the polyatomic case, that would leave no way to account \
for bonding to the second hydrogen. Instead, we we use an ",
 StyleBox["sp",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " hybrid orbital to describe contributions from Be,"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814271296484496*^9, 3.8142713694626055`*^9}, {
  3.81427141293372*^9, 3.814271520658491*^9}, {3.8142766119246464`*^9, 
  3.814276790316574*^9}, {3.8142776932260213`*^9, 
  3.814277700008115*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"27b0ea7c-0add-4acf-affb-\
ca063978f0ba"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  SubscriptBox["\[CapitalPhi]", 
   StyleBox["sp",
    FontSlant->"Italic"]], "=", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["c",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "1"], 
    SubscriptBox["\[Phi]", 
     RowBox[{"2", 
      StyleBox["s",
       FontSlant->"Italic"]}]]}], "+", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["c",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], "2"], 
    SubscriptBox["\[Phi]", 
     RowBox[{"2", 
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["p",
        FontSlant->"Italic"], "z"]}]]}]}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8142715408501225`*^9, 3.8142716264528427`*^9}, {
   3.8142716634962983`*^9, 3.81427166385531*^9}, {3.8142717090653296`*^9, 
   3.814271758882024*^9}, {3.8142767976668887`*^9, 3.8142767986447644`*^9}, 
   3.814277116274558*^9},ExpressionUUID->"1426ecf5-bffe-40d9-99fd-\
6dde64212433"],

Cell["\<\
We actually want to construct two of these hybrid orbitals, one for each bond \
to a hydrogen, so we write\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814277129767643*^9, 3.8142771749194093`*^9}, {
  3.8142776781895514`*^9, 
  3.814277678662664*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"d427b3ef-8791-4808-b3ab-\
04a063094b63"],

