Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Bonding in Conjugated and Aromatic Systems", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8144282202558775`*^9, 
  3.814428226315092*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"3537ab04-bb1d-49d5-9875-\
3937c5b394a3"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Introduction to H\[UDoubleDot]ckel Theory", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.814429104786857*^9, 3.8144291155315685`*^9}, {
  3.8145142099068394`*^9, 
  3.8145142191297913`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a43f594f-70c6-401b-b983-\
bb39fdf2dd2b"],

Cell["\<\
We now turn our attention to conjugated and aromatic hydrocarbon systems, \
such as ethene, buta-1,3-diene, and benzene (Figure 11.5). These molecules \
exhibit delocalized \[Pi] bonding, and, because the molecules are planar, we \
can make the approximation that the \[Sigma] and \[Pi] bonds are orthogonal \
and can therefore be treated separately. This approximation is known as H\
\[UDoubleDot]ckel theory, and we will now examine some of the more \
quantitative aspects of this approach.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8144291178000655`*^9, 3.814429133758173*^9}, {
  3.814429233698082*^9, 3.814429239011598*^9}, {3.814429269746044*^9, 
  3.8144293233466*^9}, {3.814429450466649*^9, 3.8144297967161655`*^9}, {
  3.814429850213069*^9, 3.814429957508636*^9}, {3.814430043901208*^9, 
  3.814430045798601*^9}, {3.8144300883717656`*^9, 3.814430090176758*^9}, {
  3.9388709030606823`*^9, 
  3.938870903219246*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8d6392b8-a750-4aaf-98b4-\
3630945ef67a"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

